<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,191,2024]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,1837,1863]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet refers to the very distinctive golden pilosity present on the abdomen of both sexes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,191,2024]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,1917,1943]" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">Remarks.</emphasis>
The golden pilosity present on this species is unique among 
<taxonomicName box="[1040,1172,1918,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Athericidae" genus="Dasyomma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1040,1172,1918,1943]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="34">Dasyomma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and gives the species a very distinctive appearance. I have not examined the male genitalia of this species, as this has not been done for most of the described species, but is advisable when the genus is revised in the future.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
